 <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.growthspurts.com/drivee/images/434360233606.jpg"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#b9a1d0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=dbc67@religiousdebate60574>DBC67</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Convicted Skeptic</span><br>  Posts: 96<br> <font color=#3333ff>(1/10/03 10:26 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=55.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: faith healing - </span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> they dont accept the premise on which the miracles are based. That God exists and that he has an individual plan for each of us. So even faith and prayers can not change that plan.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> <br>
Wouldn’t that be the basis of foreordained destiny and invalidates the whole need for free will?  The point of an experiment is to test a premise.  If it blindly accepted that faith healed, there’d be no point in the experiment.  You perform the experiment to test the hypothesis, if the best explanation is ‘god did it’ then that is the result.<br>
<br>
Since we are all sharing our stories, I will too.  My mother was diagnosed with lymphatic cancer in 1981.  The chemo/radiation field was still new and experimental in their treatments.  She was given a year to live.  My mom was a strong and determined woman, she went to 7 different oncologists and they all agreed.  18 years later she was still kicking around.  Her cancer was carved out, she got breast cancer, and a mastectomy, and skin cancer, and bone cancer, and on and on.  However, she had all this stuff she wanted to do before she died.  Learn to paint, travel to a list of places, see friends, finish her genealogy, get her estate in order.  She battled and beat the odds over and over.  I went on to work in oncologic pharmaceuticals because of her fight.  I also confirmed while working in military hospitals what my grandfather had always told my dad and he told me.  Once a person has given up, there is nothing the physician can do to save them, and that if the person is still fighting, there is almost no end to what can be done, he was an army surgeon.  <br>
<br>
In 1999, the day before my father’s birthday, she died.  Her estate was in order, many of her paintings we in all her kid’s houses, she had been all over the world and everything for her genealogy was assembled (though not written out and charted, but gathered.)  My father had several strokes the previous few years and was hospitalized and in a care facility at the time.  He had lost the ability to speak to the strokes and his left leg to vascular atrophy.  We couldn’t tell him his wife of almost 50 years died on his birthday, so we kept it from him a few days.  When he found out, that was the end for him.  A few months later, he too died.<br>
<br>
Human beings are amazing things, astonishing in will and tenacity.  We needn’t look to the skies when our answers are right here.  My parents were amazing people.  The cards they got dealt were pretty raw.  If that is just random chance, then they did really well with what they got dealt.  If it was god's plan, he is an asshole.<br>
 <p>DBC67<br>
