<br>
If you accept the premise that G-d intervened to get your friend pregnant, then you have to accept that G-d also intervenes and causes miscarriages, stillbirths, and other horrific events. And I don't think &quot;We don't understand His ways &quot; is a valid point, although I know from the pastor who visited me in the hospital after our baby died, that it's a pretty standard answer.<br>
<br>
If you go with that premise, I don't see how you get to reconcile it with a one way street of positives only. You have to take both sides of the coin, and that doesn't paint quite the pretty picture.<br>
<br>
For beating the odds, after our late term loss, I was told that my chances of having just one healthy baby were under 20%, probably lower in the literature on my disorder. I had three. Your friend's chances of achieving pregnancy were severely limited by her condition. I get that. But things like that happen all the time, and I don't see the leap to assuming a higher power stepped in....<br>
<br>
Jessica<br>
