<br>
I doubt very greatly that the docs told her that all scientific studies concluded that she had a zero percent probability of pregnancy. If they did, then they weren't following the scientific process. <br>
<br>
I bet they told her there was little to no chance, because that would be more in keeping with the doctors I know, and with what I  know about how science/medicine is practiced. It's also a common finding in severely advanced endometriosis. Unlikely, but possible.<br>
<br>
Science doesn't know everything. More importantly, science doesn't claim to know everything. Science is the simply the best tool we have to getting down the things we know, and finding the answers, reliable answers that can be repeated and verified independently.<br>
<br>
I don't see how your friend's situation overrules the application of science. Human bodies have differences. That's why I would find it very hard to believe that she was told absolutely not, no way. Science isn't usually limiting in that form.<br>
<br>
Had she had her uterus removed, that I could see. But I assume when she was told that it would be nigh impossible, the doctors were going off predictive values for patients they had seen with similiar predicaments...<br>
<br>
