&quot;The last time religion ruled the world it was known as the <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Dark Ages</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->.&quot;</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#9fb7df><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> Double Latte</span><br> <span class=usertitle>Unregistered User</span><br>   <font color=#3333ff>(1/10/03 2:58 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=55.topic&index=14>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Significance</span><hr size=1> DBC, I printed out the looong essay and read it over. It got me thinking about these issues and here is my comment - I hope I don't ramble:<br>
<br>
Human beings love significance. If something has no immediate significance, they will look hard until they can find some connection or coincidence to create significance. It helps us feel better when we try to make some sense out of our disorderly world.<br>
<br>
For example, I lost a baby in 2000, and the way I lost him (as I've detailed in recent threads here) could mean if there is a god, that baby was His way of flipping me the bird BIG TIME.  But if I wish to attach significance to my loss, I can still find ways to do so.<br>
<br>
If I hadn't lost that baby, I would never have given birth to the lovely little baby I have now. Therefore, I can choose to believe the loss of my first son was &quot;necessary&quot; for the birth of my second son.  This attaches a &quot;reason&quot; to my horrible loss, making it emotionally more bearable. It justifies my loss, creating a sort of ex post facto consolation.<br>
<br>
We humans also love to find coincidences and use them as &quot;proof&quot; of significance, &quot;god's intervention&quot; and so on. Example: My LMP date for my living baby's conception is the same day my husband and I attended an All Souls Day ceremony honoring the baby I lost (along with all other parish members lost that year.) I had been trying to get pregnant again for nearly 9 months, and THAT was the month it finally happened. A coincidence, but I could attach significance to if I chose.<br>
<br>
I'd had many nightmares after my loss, and in one of them I dreamed my lost baby was still inside me and that was why I couldn't get pregnant. After that dream I realized I needed to &quot;let go of him&quot; emotionally and I was finally able to conceive that month.  I think our brains know much more about our bodies than we are conscious of, and I think that sort of knowledge and its consequences get attributed to &quot;god.&quot; <br>
<br>
I also think that when things happen that we don't understand, it's easier to attibute it to &quot;god&quot; then say &quot;I don't get that.&quot;<br>
<br>
Okay, I am starting to ramble here so I'll stop.<br>
<br>
DL <br>
<br>
